title: Six Dead, Hundreds Injured After Tornado Tears Through Southern Brazil | 10 News
description: A powerful tornado swept through southern Brazil on Friday, killing six people and injuring at least 750 in Rio Bonito do Iguacu. The state government declared three days of mourning and a state of public calamity, allowing access to emergency funds. Approximately 1,000 people were forced into temporary shelters in nearby Laranjeiras do Sul, as entire neighbourhoods were destroyed. Winds of up to 250 km/h damaged almost 90 per cent of the town’s buildings, and rescue teams worked through the night to clear debris and restore essential services. title: Philippines Faces Super Typhoon Fung-Wong Days After Deadly Kalmaegi | 10 News
description: The Philippines is being lashed by strong winds and heavy rain as Typhoon Fung-wong nears the northern islands, forcing over 100,000 people to evacuate. The storm comes days after an earlier typhoon, Kalmaegi, which left a trail of destruction and more than 200 people dead. Known locally as Uwan, Fung-wong carries sustained winds of 185 km/h and gusts up to 230 km/h, and is expected to make landfall in Aurora province in central Luzon on Sunday night. title: Victoria Police Launch Sweeping Crackdown In Australia’s New Crime Capital | 10 News
description: In the nation's new crime capital, Victoria Police have launched a sweeping crackdown in Melbourne's west. They arrested more than a dozen people during a two-day blitz, including a driver accused of ramming a police car before officers found drugs, cash and a handgun. title: Princess Anne Attends Remembrance Sunday Service During Sydney Visit | 10 News
description: Princess Anne pulled on her army greens to meet hundreds of Australian servicemen and women during a day of official duties in Sydney. title: Liberal Senator Andrew Bragg Threatens To Quit Frontbench If Net Zero Policy Is Dropped | 10 News
description: A prominent Liberal senator has threatened to quit the front bench if the party walks away from its international commitment to cut greenhouse gas emissions and combat global warming. title: Oscar Piastri Crashes Out As Lando Norris Extends F1 Championship Lead In Brazil GP | 10 News
description: Oscar Piastri started the Brazil weekend one point behind Lando Norris, and has now slipped even further behind in the race for the Formula 1 World Championship. The Aussie crashed out of the Sprint race in Brazil and only managed fourth in qualifying. The race was then won by his teammate, with Lando Norris then nailing pole for tomorrow's main event. title: NSW Police And Premier Chris Minns Up Against Legal Minefield Over Neo-Nazi Rally | 10 News+
description: New South Wales residents are shocked after it was revealed that police allowed a Neo-Nazi protest outside the State Parliament in Sydney. Premier Chris Minns and NSW Police now face a legal minefield, as they determine whether or not the ‘White Australia’ group broke any racial vilification laws. The Premier hopes to add to existing laws, or make new ones, to stop the far-right white supremacist group from rallying again. title: Neo-Nazis Outside NSW Parliament, US Government Shutdown, Princess Anne In Australia | 10 News+
description: Despite the growing split in the Coalition over net zero policy, a Liberal MP has joined her Nationals colleague in a stunning musical performance in Parliament. Angie Bell played the saxophone while Sam Birrell took on the vocals, singing “they can never tear us apart”. 10 News+ spoke to Angie Bell about the unexpected display of unity.  New South Wales residents are shocked after it was revealed that police allowed a Neo-Nazi protest outside the State Parliament in Sydney. Premier Chris Minns and NSW Police now face a legal minefield, as they determine whether or not the ‘White Australia’ group broke any racial vilification laws. The Premier hopes to add to existing laws, or make new ones, to stop the far-right white supremacist group from rallying again.  The United States’ first government shutdown in seven years is now entering its 39th day, eclipsing the previous record. The shutdown is not only crippling the US economy, but is also causing flight chaos, forcing over 700,000 public servants to work without pay, and leaving up to 41 million Americans who usually rely on food stamps to miss meals.  Australia’s whale-watching community is excited over the spotting of a young albino whale off the country’s east coast. The one-year-old humpback named Siale was born in Tonga and is currently cruising north, last spotted heading to Sydney. White whales are incredibly rare, with the last known example in the Pacific Ocean not having been spotted for five years.
